      "modelAnswer": "The AIV test measures how much an aggregate resists SUDDEN IMPACT (shock loading). A heavy hammer is dropped freely from a fixed height 15 times onto the aggregate, and the percentage of material crushed (passing 2.36 mm sieve) is reported as the AIV.\n\nReal-life comparison:\n- ACV test = like slowly pressing your hand down on an egg (gradual load). It tests resistance to sustained compressive pressure.\n- AIV test = like suddenly dropping a hammer on the egg (sudden shock). It tests resistance to sudden impact.\n\nKey differences:\nFeature | ACV | AIV\nLoad type | Gradual (10 min) | Sudden (15 hammer blows)\nLoad amount | 400 kN total | 15 free falls of hammer\nMeasures | Crushing strength | Impact/shock resistance\n\nWhy AIV matters: In road construction, industrial floors, and areas with heavy machinery or vehicle movement, aggregates face dynamic impact loads repeatedly. For such applications, AIV is equally or more important than ACV. For normal building structures, both tests together give a complete picture of aggregate toughness."
