      "modelAnswer": "Fineness of cement refers to how finely it has been ground. It is measured as surface area per unit weight (m²/kg) using Blaine's method.\n\nWhy fineness matters:\n- Cement hardens by reacting with water (hydration). Finer cement has more surface area exposed to water, so it reacts faster and more completely.\n- Finer cement gives: higher early strength, less bleeding, more cohesive mix, better surface finish.\n- IS minimum: OPC 43 and OPC 53 must have ≥ 225 m²/kg. Typical production range: 290–390 m²/kg.\n\nIf cement is too coarse:\n- Slower hydration — early-age strength (1-day, 3-day) is lower.\n- More bleeding occurs — water rises to surface, weakening the top layer.\n- Harder to get smooth surface finish on concrete elements.\n- Less cohesive mix — more segregation risk.\n\nPractical note: Cement fineness is reported in the weekly Mill Test Certificate (MTC). Plant teams should review MTC to anticipate any changes in water demand or early strength performance."
