      "modelAnswer": "An admixture is a chemical added to concrete (apart from cement, aggregate, and water) in small quantities to improve certain properties of the concrete.\n\nWater reduction is the key property of plasticizers/superplasticizers. It is the percentage by which water can be reduced in a concrete mix while maintaining the SAME workability (slump) as a mix without admixture.\n\nExample: If a control mix without admixture needs 200 kg of water to achieve 100 mm slump, and a mix with admixture achieves the same slump with only 160 kg of water — the water reduction = (200–160)/200 × 100 = 20%.\n\nWhy it is so important for RMC:\n1. Lower water = lower water-cement ratio = HIGHER STRENGTH for same cement content.\n2. OR: Same strength with LESS CEMENT = cost saving.\n3. High workability for pumping without adding excess water.\n4. Better durability — less porous concrete.\n\nAs per ASTM C494: Type A = water reducer (>5%); Type F = High-Range Water Reducer (>12%). Superplasticizers used in RMC are typically Type F achieving 18–25% water reduction."
