      "modelAnswer": "Correct Answer: (a) Only Statement 1 is correct.\n\nStatement 1 is CORRECT. If a new lot has less water reduction, the plant needs to increase the admixture dose to maintain the designed water-cement ratio and workability. This is a temporary corrective measure. The supplier must be informed with documented test evidence and asked to match the approved specification. Higher dose = higher cost, so this should be tracked and charged back to the supplier if ongoing.\n\nStatement 2 is WRONG. Slump retention testing must ALWAYS be done by testing both the master sample and incoming lot SIMULTANEOUSLY. This is because slump loss is affected by ambient temperature, aggregate moisture, and cement reactivity — all of which change from day to day. If you test the new lot on Monday and compare with master sample data from last week, the comparison is meaningless. Only a side-by-side simultaneous test gives a valid comparison."
