      "question": "What is water-cement ratio and why should water never be added at site after the concrete truck leaves the plant? Explain using a simple example.",
      "modelAnswer": "Water-cement ratio (w/c) = Total water in the mix ÷ Weight of cement.\n\nIt is the single most important factor controlling concrete strength. Lower w/c = stronger, denser, more durable concrete.\n\nExample: A mix designed for M30 at w/c = 0.45 uses 350 kg cement and 157 kg water. If 20 litres of water is added at site:\nNew water = 177 kg → New w/c = 177/350 = 0.506.\n\nThis small addition of 20 litres raises w/c from 0.45 to 0.51 — and typically reduces 28-day strength by 4–6 MPa. The concrete may no longer meet the M30 requirement.\n\nOther harms of adding water at site:\n- Increases bleeding (water rises to top, creating a weak dusty surface layer).\n- Increases drying shrinkage cracks.\n- Increases permeability — reduces durability of the structure.\n- Dilutes the admixture effect — concrete becomes segregated.\n\nThe admixture in the mix is specifically designed to give workability WITHOUT needing extra water. Adding water wastes the admixture and undoes the mix design. Always reject this practice at site."
